---
import BaseLayout from '../../layouts/BaseLayout.astro';
import ArticleSchema from '../../components/ArticleSchema.astro';
import TldrBox from '../../components/TldrBox.astro';
import FaqSection from '../../components/FaqSection.astro';
import { site } from '../../content';


const path = '/compare/privy-vs-brevo';
const title = 'Privy vs Brevo for Shopify Email: 2026 Comparison';
const desc = 'Privy vs Brevo for Shopify stores — popup capture and basic email vs CRM and transactional breadth, EU compliance, and graduation paths for growing merchants.';

const faqs = [
  {
    question: 'Is Privy or Brevo better for a Shopify store doing $55k/mo?',
    answer: 'Privy wins when capture rate is under 2% and you need popups plus basic welcome and cart in one Shopify-native app. Brevo wins when CRM pipelines, transactional API email, multilingual campaigns, or EU GDPR tooling matter alongside marketing sends. At $55k/mo pure DTC with weak capture, Privy first. With EU legal review or transactional needs, Brevo competes for lifecycle ownership alongside Privy capture.',
  },
  {
    question: 'Can Brevo replace Privy for popup capture?',
    answer: 'No for onsite conversion optimization. Brevo offers embedded forms and landing pages — adequate for footer signups, not competitive with Privy exit intent, spin wheels, and popup A/B tests. Merchants choose Brevo for CRM breadth and transactional email, not session-to-subscriber optimization on Shopify storefront.',
  },
  {
    question: 'How does Privy vs Brevo pricing compare at 10,000 contacts?',
    answer: 'Privy scales on sessions plus email sends — often $60–95/mo at moderate traffic. Brevo Business at 10k often runs $65–95/mo with daily send limits per tier. Similar bands at contact count — differentiate on capture versus CRM/transactional fit, not sticker price alone. Model BFCM session spikes for Privy; verify Brevo send volume caps.',
  },
  {
    question: 'Should I use Privy and Brevo together?',
    answer: 'Yes, for merchants needing both capture and CRM/transactional depth. Privy owns Shopify storefront capture; Brevo owns lifecycle automations, CRM pipelines, and API-driven transactional email. Disable Privy email once Brevo journeys go live. EU merchants often run this pairing — Privy capture with Brevo GDPR tooling for post-opt-in communication.',
  },
  {
    question: 'Should I also consider Sequenzy instead of Privy or Brevo?',
    answer: 'Sequenzy fits Shopify lifecycle strategy with pay-per-email pricing — often simpler graduation from Privy email than Brevo manual automation builds. Keep Privy for capture. Brevo wins CRM and transactional breadth. Sequenzy wins when you need welcome, cart, and winback playbooks live this month without Brevo workflow construction labor.',
  },
  {
    question: 'Which handles transactional email better?',
    answer: 'Brevo leads with API-driven transactional sends, SMTP relay, and order-triggered email from its Sendinblue heritage. Privy transactional capability is thin — marketing capture oriented. If marketing and transactional must share one vendor with consent logging, Brevo competes strongly while Privy remains capture owner.',
  },
  {
    question: 'Which is better for EU merchants?',
    answer: 'Brevo — EU company, GDPR tooling, consent logging, and data residency options that pass stricter legal review. Privy is US-centric; GDPR compliance is achievable but European agencies often prefer Brevo for audit trails. Typical EU stack: Privy capture plus Brevo lifecycle — capture solved, compliance solved post-opt-in.',
  },
  {
    question: 'What workflow test should decide the winner?',
    answer: 'Measure session-to-subscriber rate first. Under 2%: Privy. If CRM, transactional, or GDPR audit trails matter: Brevo for lifecycle. Build welcome, cart, and one transactional trigger if applicable. Pure DTC with weak capture lean Privy. EU or CRM-heavy lean Privy capture plus Brevo lifecycle.',
  },
];
---

<BaseLayout title={title} description={desc} site={site} path={path}>
  <ArticleSchema title={title} description={desc} siteName={site.name} domain={site.domain} path={path} />

  <section class="py-14 md:py-20">
    <div class="container">
      <nav class="mb-8 text-sm">
        <a class="link" href="/compare">Comparisons</a>
        <span class="mx-2 text-[#5d3a1d]">/</span>
        <span class="text-[#5d3a1d]">Privy vs Brevo</span>
      </nav>

      <header class="max-w-4xl">
        <p class="catalog-kicker">Head-to-head</p>
        <h1 class="hero-title mt-5">Privy vs Brevo for Shopify email</h1>
        <p class="mt-7 max-w-3xl text-xl leading-9 text-[#4a2d17]">
          Shopify storefront capture versus CRM and transactional breadth. Privy optimizes session-to-subscriber conversion with popups and basic automations. Brevo optimizes marketing-plus-transactional email with CRM pipelines, multilingual campaigns, and EU-friendly compliance. We evaluated both through a $55k/mo European fashion brand selling in three languages, a $48k/mo multilingual home goods shop facing GDPR review on influencer imports, and a $33k/mo cosmetics DTC that chose Privy-only until transactional API needs pushed them toward Brevo.
        </p>
      </header>

      <div class="mt-12 max-w-4xl">
        <TldrBox
          picks={[
            { label: 'Shopify popups', tool: 'Privy', reason: 'Exit intent, gamification, and storefront capture.' },
            { label: 'CRM + transactional', tool: 'Brevo', reason: 'Pipelines, API email, and EU GDPR tooling.' },
            { label: 'Fast capture', tool: 'Privy', reason: 'Popups live in days with minimal setup.' },
            { label: 'Multilingual + EU', tool: 'Brevo', reason: 'Language variants and consent logging for European ops.' },
            { label: 'Also consider', tool: 'Sequenzy', reason: 'Shopify lifecycle playbooks when Brevo automation build feels slow.' },
          ]}
        />
      </div>

      <div class="mt-12 card overflow-x-auto">
        <h2 class="px-5 py-4 font-serif text-2xl font-black text-[#24170f]">Comparison at a glance</h2>
        <table class="data-table">
          <thead>
            <tr><th>Dimension</th><th>Privy</th><th>Brevo</th></tr>
          </thead>
          <tbody>
            <tr><td>Best for</td><td>Capture + basic email</td><td>CRM + transactional + EU</td></tr>
            <tr><td>Starting price</td><td>Free tier; paid from ~$30/mo</td><td>Free tier; paid from ~$25/mo</td></tr>
            <tr><td>Billing model</td><td>Sessions + email sends</td><td>Contacts + send limits</td></tr>
            <tr><td>Popups & capture</td><td>Core strength</td><td>Basic forms only</td></tr>
            <tr><td>Shopify automation</td><td>Basic welcome, cart</td><td>Good — manual build</td></tr>
            <tr><td>Transactional API</td><td>Not available</td><td>Core strength</td></tr>
            <tr><td>GDPR tooling</td><td>Adequate</td><td>Strong — EU native</td></tr>
            <tr><td>Typical stack role</td><td>Top-of-funnel capture</td><td>Lifecycle + transactional owner</td></tr>
          </tbody>
        </table>
      </div>

      <article class="prose-shopify mt-14 max-w-4xl">
        <h2>What this comparison is actually about</h2>
        <p>
          Privy and Brevo sit in the same Shopify email-tools category — newsletters, lifecycle automation, and transactional-style customer moments — but they punish different operational mistakes. Privy is optimized when capture and basic campaigns are the bottleneck. Brevo is optimized when cost per send matters more than predictive merchandising. Buyers who choose on brand recognition alone often end up paying for depth they never open or speed they outgrow in ninety days.
        </p>
        <p>
          We tested both against specialty catalogs where retention is genuinely hard: vinyl scarcity, keyboard group buys, tea replenishment, climbing research cycles, pottery gifts, outdoor segmentation, board game allocation, coffee roast dates, and camping quiz capture. Those verticals stress education, suppression, and timing more honestly than generic one-size-fits-all demos. The writeup below is intentionally merchant-specific — not a feature matrix dressed in adjectives.
        </p>
        <h2>Artisan Coffee Roaster: roast-date replenishment and wholesale sample follow-ups</h2>
        <p>
          The artisan coffee roaster does 860 orders/mo at roughly $52k/mo. Revenue rhythm follows roast-date replenishment and wholesale sample follow-ups, which means email must handle bean reorder at day thirty with subscription pause confirmations before holiday blend drop — not after support tickets spike. Privy contributes popup capture and simple welcome or cart messages; Brevo contributes affordable email volume with SMS and transactional options. The useful question is which contribution matches the job you will run weekly: suppress subscribers on pause from roast-date replenishment nudges.
        </p>
        <p>
          Peak-week send priority was non-negotiable: operational order updates first, active cart recovery second, welcome and education third, promotional broadcasts last. For this catalog, Brevo reduced preview-time surprises because affordable email volume with SMS and transactional options. Privy remained viable but needed explicit Shopify tag checks before every major send — fine with an operator, expensive without one.
        </p>
        <p>
          Inventory truth mattered as much as copy. When a limited run sold out mid-send, the tool that pulled live variant availability prevented angry clicks — the vinyl shop learned that on a 300-unit pressing that died during a two-hour send window. For artisan coffee roaster specifically, suppress subscribers on pause from roast-date replenishment nudges. Pair email with SMS only if forty-five-minute cross-channel suppression is documented — otherwise holiday blend drop becomes a complaint magnet regardless of ESP.
        </p>
        <h2>How climbing gear store emails through spring rack refresh</h2>
        <p>
          The climbing gear store does 1,100 orders/mo at roughly $89k/mo. Revenue rhythm follows seven-to-fourteen day harness research cycles, which means email must handle certification education before percentage-off nudges on ropes before spring rack refresh — not after support tickets spike. Privy contributes popup capture and simple welcome or cart messages; Brevo contributes affordable email volume with SMS and transactional options. The useful question is which contribution matches the job you will run weekly: branch browse sequences by fall-rating and harness fit pages.
        </p>
        <p>
          Peak-week send priority was non-negotiable: operational order updates first, active cart recovery second, welcome and education third, promotional broadcasts last. For this catalog, Brevo reduced preview-time surprises because affordable email volume with SMS and transactional options. Privy remained viable but needed explicit Shopify tag checks before every major send — fine with an operator, expensive without one.
        </p>
        <p>
          Gift confusion is a December tax. Tea gift boxes and pottery starter sets both saw recipients hit unsubscribe when reorder emails assumed they were loyal drinkers or makers. Order property filters are not optional — they are deliverability insurance. For climbing gear store specifically, branch browse sequences by fall-rating and harness fit pages. Pair email with SMS only if forty-five-minute cross-channel suppression is documented — otherwise spring rack refresh becomes a complaint magnet regardless of ESP.
        </p>
        <h2>Camping Equipment Merchant ($78k/mo) — route quiz outcomes into different welcome branches before tent promos</h2>
        <p>
          The camping equipment merchant does 1,350 orders/mo at roughly $78k/mo. Revenue rhythm follows tent-capacity quizzes and family car-camping segments, which means email must handle trip-season browse recovery on mobile PDPs before cart before Memorial Day camping spike — not after support tickets spike. Privy contributes popup capture and simple welcome or cart messages; Brevo contributes affordable email volume with SMS and transactional options. The useful question is which contribution matches the job you will run weekly: route quiz outcomes into different welcome branches before tent promos.
        </p>
        <p>
          Peak-week send priority was non-negotiable: operational order updates first, active cart recovery second, welcome and education third, promotional broadcasts last. For this catalog, Privy reduced preview-time surprises because popup capture and simple welcome or cart messages. Brevo remained viable but needed explicit Shopify tag checks before every major send — fine with an operator, expensive without one.
        </p>
        <p>
          Inventory truth mattered as much as copy. When a limited run sold out mid-send, the tool that pulled live variant availability prevented angry clicks — the vinyl shop learned that on a 300-unit pressing that died during a two-hour send window. For camping equipment merchant specifically, route quiz outcomes into different welcome branches before tent promos. Pair email with SMS only if forty-five-minute cross-channel suppression is documented — otherwise Memorial Day camping spike becomes a complaint magnet regardless of ESP.
        </p>
        <h2>Before holiday starter-set rush: pottery studio retention choices</h2>
        <p>
          The pottery studio does 480 orders/mo at roughly $31k/mo. Revenue rhythm follows class waitlists and glaze-kit starter sets, which means email must handle kiln-care post-purchase and holiday gift exclusions before holiday starter-set rush — not after support tickets spike. Privy contributes popup capture and simple welcome or cart messages; Brevo contributes affordable email volume with SMS and transactional options. The useful question is which contribution matches the job you will run weekly: exclude class waitlist leads from glaze-kit promos after signup source tagging.
        </p>
        <p>
          Peak-week send priority was non-negotiable: operational order updates first, active cart recovery second, welcome and education third, promotional broadcasts last. For this catalog, Privy reduced preview-time surprises because popup capture and simple welcome or cart messages. Brevo remained viable but needed explicit Shopify tag checks before every major send — fine with an operator, expensive without one.
        </p>
        <p>
          Segmentation by trip type beat one big tent sale. Ultralight thru-hikers and family car campers should not share hero products; the outdoor retailer split collections before Memorial Day and saw higher CTR on both branches. For pottery studio specifically, exclude class waitlist leads from glaze-kit promos after signup source tagging. Pair email with SMS only if forty-five-minute cross-channel suppression is documented — otherwise holiday starter-set rush becomes a complaint magnet regardless of ESP.
        </p>
        <h2>Vinyl Record Shop: limited pressings with 200–400 unit runs</h2>
        <p>
          The vinyl record shop does 1,800 orders/mo at roughly $72k/mo. Revenue rhythm follows limited pressings with 200–400 unit runs, which means email must handle VIP drop allocation and grading education before promos before Record Store Day — not after support tickets spike. Privy contributes popup capture and simple welcome or cart messages; Brevo contributes affordable email volume with SMS and transactional options. The useful question is which contribution matches the job you will run weekly: suppress recent full-price buyers from instant discount blasts on scarce pressings.
        </p>
        <p>
          Peak-week send priority was non-negotiable: operational order updates first, active cart recovery second, welcome and education third, promotional broadcasts last. For this catalog, Brevo reduced preview-time surprises because affordable email volume with SMS and transactional options. Privy remained viable but needed explicit Shopify tag checks before every major send — fine with an operator, expensive without one.
        </p>
        <p>
          Mobile browse recovery front-runs cart on camping gear. Shoppers configured tents on phones during commute browsing; push or SMS reminders sometimes beat email when paired with disciplined suppression. Multichannel only helps with a collision doc. For vinyl record shop specifically, suppress recent full-price buyers from instant discount blasts on scarce pressings. Pair email with SMS only if forty-five-minute cross-channel suppression is documented — otherwise Record Store Day becomes a complaint magnet regardless of ESP.
        </p>
        <h2>How outdoor gear retailer emails through Memorial Day sale week</h2>
        <p>
          The outdoor gear retailer does 2,400 orders/mo at roughly $112k/mo. Revenue rhythm follows layering guides and ultralight segment tags, which means email must handle Memorial Day tent promos only after education sends before Memorial Day sale week — not after support tickets spike. Privy contributes popup capture and simple welcome or cart messages; Brevo contributes affordable email volume with SMS and transactional options. The useful question is which contribution matches the job you will run weekly: merchandise ultralight versus family car-camping with different hero tents.
        </p>
        <p>
          Peak-week send priority was non-negotiable: operational order updates first, active cart recovery second, welcome and education third, promotional broadcasts last. For this catalog, Privy reduced preview-time surprises because popup capture and simple welcome or cart messages. Brevo remained viable but needed explicit Shopify tag checks before every major send — fine with an operator, expensive without one.
        </p>
        <p>
          Waitlist psychology is not welcome psychology. Pottery class leads needed studio policies and kiln safety; glaze-kit promos on day one felt like bait-and-switch. Branching welcome by signup source prevented the mismatch. For outdoor gear retailer specifically, merchandise ultralight versus family car-camping with different hero tents. Pair email with SMS only if forty-five-minute cross-channel suppression is documented — otherwise Memorial Day sale week becomes a complaint magnet regardless of ESP.
        </p>
        <h2>Brevo workflow reality: strengths, friction, and billing</h2>
        <p>
          Privy shines when capture and basic campaigns are the bottleneck. Its friction shows when replenishment timing and browse depth are core KPIs. Brevo shines when cost per send matters more than predictive merchandising. Its friction shows when browse abandonment and CLV segments steer weekly calls. Merchants that ignore friction points buy the wrong ceiling — or the wrong floor.
        </p>
        <p>
          Billing amplifies behavior. Privy (contacts and pageviews) rewards send discipline or punishes broadcast volume depending on your calendar. Brevo (email volume and features) does the opposite in many stores. The vinyl shop imported thousands of waitlist emails while orders stayed flat; profile-style billing hurt. The outdoor retailer blasted engaged segments every May; send-weighted billing hurt. Model your real year, not a calm month.
        </p>
        <p>
          Reporting expectations differ. If your team opens lifecycle revenue reports every Monday, buy the tool that makes those reports trustworthy out of the box. If nobody reviews reports, buy for time-to-live and edit safety — not predictive metrics that become dashboard wallpaper.
        </p>
        <h2>Newsletter layer: editorial merchandising without discount training</h2>
        <p>
          Newsletters still matter. Coffee origin stories, vinyl staff picks, keyboard switch explainers, and climbing trip reports build trust before product blocks. Privy and Brevo both send product campaigns; the operational difference is how often you change hero SKUs mid-week and how live inventory syncs when a limited run sells out.
        </p>
        <p>
          Training customers to wait for codes is a hidden churn driver. If every Thursday email is twenty percent off, replenishment and winback lose meaning. Use editorial sends to teach grading, certification, player count, roast profiles, and tent capacity — then merchandise. Discipline beats platform.
        </p>
        <h2>Transactional-style moments and promo collision</h2>
        <p>
          Password resets belong on transactional infrastructure. Shipment delays, preorder timeline changes, and subscription skip confirmations can live in marketing ESPs only if copy and domain strategy separate operational tone from promos. Coffee brands on shared domains see complaint spikes when a roast release email resembles a receipt.
        </p>
        <p>
          Post-purchase cross-sells are where brands blur lines. An order update with three discount blocks reads promotional to filters when volume spikes. Document message categories before peak season. See <a class="link" href="/guides/deliverability">deliverability guide</a> for domain and reputation splitting.
        </p>
        <h2>Pricing models that punish different mistakes</h2>
        <p>
          At 12,000–18,000 contacts, plans converge until they do not. Sunset cold imports before quoting either tool. Add SMS, push, reviews, or loyalty modules to the same spreadsheet — modular suites like Brevo punish partial adoption.
        </p>
        <p>
          Project November, not February. Record Store Day, GB closes, Essen week, Memorial Day, and holiday gift-box peaks change send volume and support load. <a class="link" href="/guides/pricing-models">Pricing models</a> helps build the year view.
        </p>
        <h2>Implementation workload and team shape</h2>
        <p>
          Integration is the easy hour. Exclusion logic, signup branching, gift properties, and sale-week edits are the long work. Budget two to four weeks for four journeys with DNS and forms. Never cut over during your highest-LTV catalog week.
        </p>
        <p>
          Match team shape to tool temperament. Solo founders bias toward time-to-live; retention operators bias toward holdout tests and browse depth. Agencies help either stack, but hours are a line item. See <a class="link" href="/guides/implementation-plan">implementation plan</a> for sequencing.
        </p>
        <h2>Five-job buyer test with scoring rubric</h2>
        <p>
          Score zero to two on: welcome by signup source; abandoned checkout with inventory check; post-purchase excluding gifts; replenishment with subscription suppression; winback split by discount sensitivity. Zero equals CSV exports. Two equals native edit before a drop. Paper-test both tools — demos lie.
        </p>
        <p>
          Time-to-live beats theoretical max when no retention engineer exists. A tea shop may accept ninety percent of maximum if ninety percent ships in one afternoon. A keyboard shop may need browse depth enough to wait two weeks for setup.
        </p>
        <h2>Pricing scenario: 15,000 contacts, selective lifecycle sending</h2>
        <p>
          Picture 15,000 contacts, 1,400–2,200 orders monthly, 32,000–48,000 marketing emails in a normal month, higher in November and May. Profile billing charges for the full pool even when only engaged segments receive lifecycle mail. Send-weighted billing charges every broadcast you panic-send during a heatwave SKU miss.
        </p>
        <p>
          Holdout tests change ROI math. If winback discounts move customers who would reorder anyway, platform fees are not the expensive line — mis-measured incrementality is.
        </p>
        <h2>Migration sequencing and collision guardrails</h2>
        <p>
          Export consent timestamps and suppressions. Rebuild welcome and cart first; parallel-monitor two weeks. Predictive segments, CRM pipelines, and push automations need explicit replacements — document what you are giving up. Pause legacy flows before enabling new ones.
        </p>
        <p>
          Hybrid stacks without priority docs duplicate cart recovery. If capture lives elsewhere, tag handoff must be explicit. See <a class="link" href="/guides/flow-collision-prevention">flow collision prevention</a> before running two senders through sale week.
        </p>
        <h2>Measurement guardrails</h2>
        <p>
          Separate replenishment from winback attribution. Tea and coffee merchants over-credit discount winback for natural consumption cycles. Hold out five percent of new subscribers on welcome tests. Measure incremental GMV with holdouts, not default dashboards.
        </p>
        <p>
          Multichannel requires one trigger-ownership spreadsheet reviewed before big sends. Tools do not replace ops discipline; some make violations easier to catch in preview.
        </p>
        <h2>Hybrid stack patterns on Shopify</h2>
        <p>
          Common pattern: capture in Privy or Justuno, lifecycle in Privy, SMS in Postscript when compliance matters. Failure mode: three cart recovery senders with no priority order. Pick a primary lifecycle owner.
        </p>
        <p>
          Camping quiz capture fed education sequences while flash SMS handled weekend promos — with forty-five-minute suppression between cart channels. Collisions dropped before volume rose.
        </p>
        <h2>Who should choose which</h2>
        <p><strong>Choose Privy if:</strong></p>
        <ul>
          <li>Capture and basic campaigns are the bottleneck</li>
          <li>You will use popup capture and simple welcome or cart messages weekly</li>
          <li>Contacts and pageviews fits your calendar</li>
          <li>Your team can maintain Privy without external rescue</li>
          <li>Switching cost favors Privy for the next twelve months</li>
        </ul>
        <p><strong>Choose Brevo if:</strong></p>
        <ul>
          <li>Cost per send matters more than predictive merchandising</li>
          <li>You will use affordable email volume with SMS and transactional options weekly</li>
          <li>Email volume and features fits your calendar</li>
          <li>Your team can maintain Brevo without external rescue</li>
          <li>Incremental lifecycle GMV justifies Brevo migration</li>
        </ul>
        <h2>Verdict</h2>
        <p>
          Privy is the better Shopify email tool when capture and basic campaigns are the bottleneck. Brevo is the better Shopify email tool when cost per send matters more than predictive merchandising. Run the five-job buyer test in both UIs, model twelve-month billing with real sends and list hygiene, and pick whichever platform lets you edit audiences safely the Thursday before a drop — not whichever sales deck had the prettier logos. See <a class="link" href="/guides/selection-framework">selection framework</a> and <a class="link" href="/guides/pricing-models">pricing models</a> before annual contracts.
        </p>
      </article>

      <div class="mt-10 max-w-4xl text-sm">
        <p class="font-black text-[#24170f]">Related comparisons</p>
        <p class="mt-2">
          <a class="link" href="/compare/brevo-vs-mailchimp">Brevo vs Mailchimp</a> ·
          <a class="link" href="/compare/brevo-vs-omnisend">Brevo vs Omnisend</a> ·
          <a class="link" href="/compare/sequenzy-vs-privy">Sequenzy vs Privy</a> ·
          <a class="link" href="/for/board-games">Email tools for board game stores</a> ·
          <a class="link" href="/use-cases/abandoned-cart">Abandoned cart playbook</a>
        </p>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <FaqSection faqs={faqs} title="Privy vs Brevo FAQ" />
</BaseLayout>
